SECURITY.md

TIDELIFT.rst
     1â†’========
     2â†’Tidelift
     3â†’========
     4â†’
     5â†’pluggy is a member of `Tidelift`_. This document describes how the core team manages
     6â†’Tidelift-related activities.
     7â†’
     8â†’What is it
     9â†’==========
    10â†’
    11â†’Tidelift aims to make Open Source sustainable by offering subscriptions to companies which rely
    12â†’on Open Source packages. This subscription allows it to pay maintainers of those Open Source
    13â†’packages to aid sustainability of the work.
    14â†’
    15â†’It is the perfect platform for companies that want to support Open Source packages and at the same
    16â†’time obtain assurances regarding maintenance, quality and security.
    17â†’
    18â†’Funds
    19â†’=====
    20â†’
    21â†’It was decided in the `mailing list`_ that the Tidelift contribution will be split evenly between
    22â†’members of the `contributors team`_ interested in receiving funding.
    23â†’
    24â†’The current list of contributors receiving funding are:
    25â†’
    26â†’* `@nicoddemus`_
    27â†’* `@The-Compiler`_
    28â†’* `@RonnyPfannschmidt`_
    29â†’
      â†’â€¦

changelog/590.trivial.rst
     1â†’The ``pluggy.__version__`` variable is now dynamically provided via a module-level ``__getattr__`` implementation, using ``importlib`` to obtain the installed version.

changelog/README.rst
     1â†’This directory contains "newsfragments" which are short files that contain a small **ReST**-formatted
     2â†’text that will be added to the next ``CHANGELOG``.
     3â†’
     4â†’The ``CHANGELOG`` will be read by users, so this description should be aimed to pytest users
     5â†’instead of describing internal changes which are only relevant to the developers.
     6â†’
     7â†’Make sure to use full sentences with correct case and punctuation, for example::
     8â†’
     9â†’    Fix issue with non-ascii messages from the ``warnings`` module.
    10â†’
    11â†’Each file should be named like ``<ISSUE>.<TYPE>.rst``, where
    12â†’``<ISSUE>`` is an issue number, and ``<TYPE>`` is one of:
    13â†’
    14â†’* ``feature``: new user facing features, like new command-line options and new behavior.
    15â†’* ``bugfix``: fixes a reported bug.
    16â†’* ``doc``: documentation improvement, like rewording an entire session or adding missing docs.
    17â†’* ``removal``: feature deprecation or removal.
    18â†’* ``vendor``: changes in packages vendored in pytest.
    19â†’* ``trivial``: fixing a small typo or internal change that might be noteworthy.
    20â†’
    21â†’So for example: ``123.feature.rst``, ``456.bugfix.rst``.
    22â†’
    23â†’If your PR fixes an issue, use that number here. If there is no issue,
    24â†’then after you submit the PR and get the PR number you can add a
    25â†’changelog using that instead.
    26â†’
    27â†’If you are not sure what issue type to use, don't hesitate to ask in your PR.
    28â†’
    29â†’``towncrier`` preserves multiple paragraphs and formatting (code blocks, lists, and so on), but for entries
    30â†’other than ``features`` it is usually better to stick to a single paragraph to keep it concise. You can install
    31â†’``towncrier`` and then run ``towncrier --draft``
    32â†’if you want to get a preview of how your change will look in the final release notes.

